      "ESSeqNum": 0,
      "FacilityID": 1000087248,
      "SummaryText": "Accidental release prevention and emergency response policies:  It is our policy to adhere to all applicable federal, state, and local laws.  If an emergency related to the ammonia or hydrogen storage systems were to occur, it is our policy to initiate our on-site emergency response program.\n\n\n\nDescription of facility and regulated substances handled:  This facility manufactures silicon carbide wafers and semiconductor devices for the microelectronic and other industries.  Hydrogen and Ammonia are used in the manufacturing process.  \n\n\n\nAmmonia is stored in two storage tanks with a total capacity of 101,987 lbs. Hydrogen is stored in a combination of tanks and storage tubes with a total capacity of 12,931 lbs.\n\n\n\nAmmonia - The worst-case release scenario is the failure of one 50,313 pound tank resulting in a vapor cloud.  Using EPA's Dense Gas Dispersion (DEGADIS) model, the distance to the toxic endpoint is 2.35 miles.  Off-site public receptors include a residential population of approximately 7500, and recreational, commercial, retail and light industrial facilities within the Research Triangle Park and the City of Durham.\n\n\n\nHydrogen - The worst-case release scenario is the failure of the 6424-pound tank resulting in a vapor cloud explosion.  Using RMPCompTM, the distance to the toxic endoint is 0.2 miles.  Off-site public receptors do not impact any major use areas.\n\n\n\nGeneral accidental release prevention program and chemical-specific prevention steps:  This facility complies with EPA's accidental prevention rule and all applicable state and local codes and regulations.  The facility has developed and implemented the requirements for an OSHA PSM Plan for the facility.\n\n\n\nFive-year accident history:  On 29 September 2018 at 0223, approximately 1104 lbs of hydrogen released at the bulk hydrogen storage process lasting approximately 3 hours and 35 minutes. The incident involved release of hydrogen to the environment, but did not result in an ignition, fire, or ex"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 1000087248,
      "SummaryText": "plosion. Cree Emergency Response Team and the Durham fire department responded to the incident. Cree Buildings 1/5/8 and 2/4/7 were evacuated and Silicon Drive (public road) was closed until the incident was resolved.\n\n\n\nEmergency response program:  In the event of an emergency involving our ammonia or hydrogen storage systems, it is Cree's policy to implement our emergency response program.  We have discussed this policy with the fire department and other pertinent officials.\n\n\n\nPlanned changes to improve safety:  This systems have been designed with redundant safety systems. Any changes to the processes due to altered production needs or continuous improvement are managed via Cree's Management of Change (MOC) program and are reviewed as part of the Process Hazard Analysis (PHA)."
    }
  ]
